Lights got sharper.

488
00:43:02,400 --> 00:43:03,811
I could see in pitch black.

489
00:43:04,920 --> 00:43:07,730
I could spot a golf ball from
a mile away and tell you the brand.

490
00:43:07,960 --> 00:43:11,442
- So the serum worked.
- Damn straight, it worked.

491
00:43:11,640 --> 00:43:14,007
Only thing is your guinea pig
can't see shit in light...

492
00:43:14,200 --> 00:43:16,806
...and my head felt like it was
about to explode or something.

493
00:43:17,000 --> 00:43:19,321
Look, we'll work
on the headaches. Okay?

494
00:43:19,560 --> 00:43:23,087
I don't think there's anything we can
do about your sensitivity to the light.

495
00:43:23,280 --> 00:43:26,363
The infrared rays from the sun just
aren't synthesizing with the serum.

496
00:43:26,560 --> 00:43:28,085
Put your head back.

497
00:43:28,960 --> 00:43:31,884
Maybe there's some kind of headgear
or something we can develop...

498
00:43:32,080 --> 00:43:34,048
...to diminish the intensity.

499
00:43:34,240 --> 00:43:35,571
Say word.

500
00:43:35,760 --> 00:43:38,240
Like I get some type of cape,
fancy car with it too?

501
00:43:38,440 --> 00:43:40,681
I bet you would just love
a theme song, wouldn't you?

502
00:43:42,800 --> 00:43:44,040
See?

503
00:43:44,240 --> 00:43:45,526
Oh, wait.

504
00:43:45,720 --> 00:43:47,961
I know I just didn't detect
a little sense of humour.

505
00:43:48,560 --> 00:43:52,087
I know Ms. Halden didn't just come up
with a little funny or something.

506
00:43:52,280 --> 00:43:53,441
It's been known to happen.

507
00:43:55,040 --> 00:43:56,201
You know what?

508
00:43:56,400 --> 00:43:58,767
I bet those cute brown eyes
get even sexier...

509
00:43:59,280 --> 00:44:01,203
...and nicer when you smile.

510
00:44:01,400 --> 00:44:02,765
How do you know
I have brown eyes?

511
00:44:03,160 --> 00:44:06,960
Snuck a peek after you drugged me
and took advantage of me.

512
00:44:07,160 --> 00:44:10,562
Mr. Connors, I wouldn't need any
anaesthesia to knock you out again.

513
00:44:11,400 --> 00:44:13,368
You're supposed to be a healer,
not a fighter.

514
00:44:13,560 --> 00:44:14,891
You're supposed to comfort me.

515
00:44:15,680 --> 00:44:18,001
What about that
doctor-patient relationship?

516
00:44:18,320 --> 00:44:19,924
Isn't there some oath
to go with that?

517
00:44:20,920 --> 00:44:22,922
I had a life before medical school,
Mr. Connors.

518
00:44:23,680 --> 00:44:25,170
On the South Side of Chicago...

519
00:44:25,360 --> 00:44:26,930
...the sisters got their own oath.

520
00:44:28,600 --> 00:44:31,365
- You want a piece of that?
- Chi-town.

521
00:44:31,560 --> 00:44:32,891
I don't want no drama.

522
00:44:33,240 --> 00:44:36,050
Hell, no. Saved by the bell.

523
00:44:36,560 --> 00:44:38,688
Let me get up until
something pop off.

524
00:44:44,320 --> 00:44:45,970
Howard, Howard, Howard.

525
00:44:46,160 --> 00:44:50,165
How did you know it was me
this time? I brushed, I flo--

526
00:44:51,240 --> 00:44:53,083
- What?
- Well.

527
00:44:53,280 --> 00:44:55,169
- Well, what?
- Well, well, well.

528
00:44:55,360 --> 00:44:59,843
Does the Conster have himself
some female companionship today?

529
00:45:00,040 --> 00:45:02,850
- Howard, could you haul ass?
- Hey, no judgment.

530
00:45:03,040 --> 00:45:06,123
Free love. That's what it was
all about in my day.

531
00:45:06,320 --> 00:45:08,243
You're a pathetic,
dirty old man, you know?

532
00:45:11,320 --> 00:45:15,450
Yeah, listen. My TV is on the fritz
and I just rented <i>Yellow submarine.</i>

533
00:45:15,640 --> 00:45:16,926
What's that have to do with me?

534
00:45:17,920 --> 00:45:19,604
Oh, well, I thought
I could borrow yours.

535
00:45:19,800 --> 00:45:22,371
It's not like you're watching it
or anything right now.

536
00:45:22,560 --> 00:45:24,369
Okay, okay. Later, later. Not now.

537
00:45:24,560 --> 00:45:26,722
Yeah, later, later.
Just give me a call...

538
00:45:26,920 --> 00:45:30,845
...when it's free and clear
down here at the love shack.

539
00:45:31,040 --> 00:45:33,168
You know, you're a
piece of work, Howard.

540
00:45:38,800 --> 00:45:41,451
- So how do you like your eggs?
- Sunny-side up.

541
00:45:42,400 --> 00:45:44,209
Too late. How about scrambled?

542
00:45:44,400 --> 00:45:45,447
Oh, damn.

543
00:45:45,880 --> 00:45:47,848
You know, Dr. Mackenzie
wanted me to apologize.

544
00:45:48,280 --> 00:45:51,284
We should have let you know there
could be side effects to the serum.

545
00:45:53,360 --> 00:45:55,124
Forget about it.
I mean, it is what it is.

546
00:45:55,320 --> 00:45:56,651
Actually, it was pretty shitty.

547
00:45:56,840 --> 00:45:58,922
But sometimes we get
so close to the project...

548
00:45:59,120 --> 00:46:01,805
...we forget that we're actually
dealing with real people.

549
00:46:02,000 --> 00:46:04,241
Look, if you hadn't been so caught up
on your work...

550
00:46:04,440 --> 00:46:06,761
...I'd never have the opportunity
to have my sight back.

551
00:46:08,080 --> 00:46:09,525
You don't know how much
that means.

552
00:46:10,840 --> 00:46:14,128
Well, we're gonna learn how
to do it better and without side effects.

553
00:46:15,160 --> 00:46:16,924
That is, if you're willing
to continue...

554
00:46:17,480 --> 00:46:19,130
You know, continue to be...

555
00:46:19,320 --> 00:46:20,321
Being your guinea pig?

556
00:46:21,160 --> 00:46:24,289
- Yeah, basically.
- I ain't got nothing to lose, baby.

557
00:46:24,480 --> 00:46:25,641
I'm a rider.

558
00:46:25,840 --> 00:46:29,925
Good. Now all we have to do
is secure the funding.

559
00:46:30,120 --> 00:46:31,724
What about Brooks?

560
00:46:31,920 --> 00:46:34,571
- Our work with Brooks is done.
- Done?

561
00:46:34,760 --> 00:46:36,888
- Yeah.
- Don't you work for the agency?

562
00:46:37,080 --> 00:46:40,766
No. When the new administration
came in, they cut us loose.

563
00:46:41,760 --> 00:46:44,081
We tried to hustle some money
from private investors...

564
00:46:44,280 --> 00:46:45,611
...but we had no takers.

565
00:46:45,800 --> 00:46:47,086
Until Brooks came along.

566
00:46:47,280 --> 00:46:50,966
He knew our work, secured the
funding, and brought us in for this job.

567
00:46:51,160 --> 00:46:53,811
And maybe, if your mission
was a success last night...

568
00:46:54,000 --> 00:46:57,163
...you can actually convince him
to continue funding the project.

569
00:46:57,360 --> 00:46:59,408
Well, we should know pretty soon.

570
00:46:59,600 --> 00:47:02,524
Brooks should be handing the brain
to the president as we speak.

571
00:47:03,360 --> 00:47:05,362
- Brain?
- Yeah. See...

572
00:47:05,560 --> 00:47:09,565
...our little mission last night
was basically to save Brooks' project.

573
00:47:09,760 --> 00:47:11,000
We sort of kind of...

574
00:47:11,600 --> 00:47:13,728
...borrowed this hard drive.

575
00:47:14,080 --> 00:47:15,844
Funny piece of equipment
for a hard drive.

576
00:47:16,080 --> 00:47:18,481
- You saw it?
- Yeah.

577
00:47:18,680 --> 00:47:21,809
While I diffused serum in your head,
Brooks took it out of the bag.

578
00:47:22,520 --> 00:47:25,205
It looked more like a thermos
than a hard drive.

579
00:47:25,400 --> 00:47:27,801
- A thermos?
- Yeah.

580
00:47:28,000 --> 00:47:31,322
It was about that big...

581
00:47:31,840 --> 00:47:33,569
...and stainless steel.

582
00:47:38,720 --> 00:47:39,767
What?

583
00:47:40,120 --> 00:47:42,885
- What?
- Peek outside.

584
00:47:43,080 --> 00:47:44,320
- Peek outside?
- Peek outside.

585
00:47:44,840 --> 00:47:46,205
All right.

586
00:47:49,400 --> 00:47:51,084
- I'm peeking outside.
- What do you see?

587
00:47:51,640 --> 00:47:53,369
"What do I see?"
I see a houseboat.

588
00:47:53,560 --> 00:47:57,201
I see a guy in a boat kind of throwing
some water out with a bucket.

589
00:47:57,400 --> 00:47:59,004
No, no, no.
Over by the bridge.

590
00:47:59,760 --> 00:48:02,206
- What do you see?
- Nothing.

591
00:48:03,880 --> 00:48:05,120
There's two guys on the bridge.

592
00:48:05,320 --> 00:48:06,765
Two--? What they got on?

593
00:48:06,960 --> 00:48:09,281
- What do you mean?
- What are they wearing?

594
00:48:09,800 --> 00:48:11,370
Dark glasses, dark suits.

595
00:48:11,720 --> 00:48:14,530
Those are Greene's men.
Get away from that window.

596
00:48:14,800 --> 00:48:16,404
Wait a minute. What's going on?

597
00:48:16,600 --> 00:48:19,444
I think something's gone wrong.
Those are agency men.

598
00:48:19,640 --> 00:48:20,880
They're staking out the place.

599
00:48:21,280 --> 00:48:23,806
- We got five minutes, if that long.
- Five minutes for what?

600
00:48:24,000 --> 00:48:27,482
- What the hell is that?
- This is my bodyguard. Let's go.

601
00:48:27,720 --> 00:48:30,041
I'm not going until you explain to me
what's going on.

602
00:48:30,320 --> 00:48:32,846
We don't have time for that.
Let's go.

603
00:48:33,040 --> 00:48:34,451
Mr. Connors, you are blind...

604
00:48:34,640 --> 00:48:37,041
...you got God knows
what arsenal in your crotch...

605
00:48:37,240 --> 00:48:39,607
...and you want me to
lead you around? I deserve answers.

606
00:48:39,800 --> 00:48:41,802
Look, Amanda,
you gotta trust me right now.

607
00:48:42,000 --> 00:48:44,162
Those men are here to kill us.
They got a hit on us.

608
00:48:44,360 --> 00:48:45,441
Let's go.

609
00:48:46,480 --> 00:48:47,891
Okay.

610
00:49:01,880 --> 00:49:03,291
Go around.

611
00:49:09,400 --> 00:49:10,890
Howard, I need a favour. Your ride.

612
00:49:11,360 --> 00:49:12,885
- What?
- Give me the damn keys!

613
00:49:14,120 --> 00:49:16,646
Yeah. I always knew
there was more to you...

614
00:49:16,840 --> 00:49:20,287
...than just a blind dude
with a rotten attitude.

615
00:49:20,480 --> 00:49:21,447
Here.

616
00:49:23,800 --> 00:49:24,961
Federal agents!

617
00:49:27,000 --> 00:49:28,365
Come out!

618
00:49:32,720 --> 00:49:34,802
Hey, Connors!

619
00:49:35,000 --> 00:49:37,367
You be careful with her.

620
00:49:37,560 --> 00:49:39,767
She's a classic.

621
00:49:50,520 --> 00:49:51,885
Get down.

622
00:50:14,840 --> 00:50:16,080
Jesus Christ.

623
00:50:22,160 --> 00:50:23,730
Yes, Mr. President?

624
00:50:24,640 --> 00:50:27,325
- Mr. President?
<i>- Guess again, Greene.</i>

625
00:50:29,080 --> 00:50:30,047
Connors.

626
00:50:30,760 --> 00:50:34,003
Don't say nothing. I got a couple
of things I need to know.

627
00:50:34,200 --> 00:50:35,929
<i>That was some stunt
you and Brooks pulled.</i>

628
00:50:36,120 --> 00:50:38,691
<i>- Tell me, how does a blind man--?</i>
- Look, don't say nothing.

629
00:50:38,880 --> 00:50:40,803
I'm asking the questions.

630
00:50:41,080 --> 00:50:42,809
Does Brooks still work
for the agency?

631
00:50:43,000 --> 00:50:45,241
Like you don't fucking know.

632
00:50:46,640 --> 00:50:49,120
Jesus Christ, you don't know.

633
00:50:50,240 --> 00:50:54,165
When the new administration came in,
Brooks' department wasn't necessary.

634
00:50:54,360 --> 00:50:56,010
We fired him about six months ago.

635
00:50:56,440 --> 00:50:57,566
<i>What did you think?</i>

636
00:50:57,760 --> 00:50:59,683
<i>You didn't work
for the U.S. Government...</i>

637
00:50:59,880 --> 00:51:01,609
...you worked for Brooks,
private citizen.

638
00:51:01,800 --> 00:51:04,690
Now he's in D.C. trying to
blackmail us with the shit you stole.

639
00:51:05,120 --> 00:51:08,806
- Is the thermos what I think it is?
- Why should I tell you anything?

640
00:51:09,000 --> 00:51:11,731
Because I'm the best chance
of you getting it back.

641
00:51:11,920 --> 00:51:13,649
Is the thermos CMC-12?

642
00:51:16,760 --> 00:51:19,491
Yes. I'm telling you, Connors,
your man's nuts.

643
00:51:19,800 --> 00:51:21,211
He went crazy when we fired him.

644
00:51:21,400 --> 00:51:23,050
All kinds of threats, accusations.

645
00:51:23,240 --> 00:51:24,844
What did you think
was gonna happen?

646
00:51:25,040 --> 00:51:26,883
That job was his whole fucking life.

647
00:51:27,200 --> 00:51:29,043
Well, now his whole life
is all fucked up.

648
00:51:29,560 --> 00:51:31,961
The man is a criminal,
he's dangerous.

649
00:51:32,160 --> 00:51:35,323
He has a vendetta against me and the
whole country and you've helped him.

650
00:51:35,520 --> 00:51:37,682
No, no, no.
He wouldn't do nothing like that.

651
00:51:37,880 --> 00:51:39,120
Nothing.

652
00:51:39,760 --> 00:51:41,250
Unless...

653
00:51:42,560 --> 00:51:43,766
You were taking him out?

654
00:51:45,440 --> 00:51:47,044
You got an executive order,
didn't you?

655
00:51:47,880 --> 00:51:50,850
Fuck you. Assassinations are
against the law in this country--

656
00:51:51,040 --> 00:51:53,202
<i>Wait. What did he threaten,
to go to the press?</i>

657
00:51:53,560 --> 00:51:56,769
To release all y'all dirty laundry
to get his job back?

658
00:51:58,280 --> 00:52:00,248
<i>No. You wouldn't go for that.</i>

659
00:52:00,600 --> 00:52:03,046
You went to the president
and got an executive order?

660
00:52:03,400 --> 00:52:04,686
You're in deep shit, Connors.

661
00:52:05,120 --> 00:52:07,691
You'd better turn yourself in and--

662
00:52:15,200 --> 00:52:16,929
- Where are we headed?
- Back to the farm...

663
00:52:17,120 --> 00:52:20,010
-...so you can reinject me with serum.
- Reinject you?

664
00:52:20,800 --> 00:52:22,325
Wait, wait a minute.

665
00:52:22,520 --> 00:52:23,851
This vehicle. Is it marked?

666
00:52:24,200 --> 00:52:25,850
What do you mean, "Is it marked?"

667
00:52:26,040 --> 00:52:28,930
Any distinctive characteristics
that will get us spotted?

668
00:52:29,560 --> 00:52:32,643
Well, yeah. There's a few.

669
00:52:32,920 --> 00:52:36,003
All right, we're gonna have to ditch
this thing. We need another ride.

670
00:52:36,240 --> 00:52:39,722
My car's still back at the farm. Are you
gonna tell me what's going on?

671
00:52:40,440 --> 00:52:43,922
Yeah. Brooks lied to us,
that's what's going on.

672
00:52:44,120 --> 00:52:46,646
- He ain't the cat we thought he was.
- Well, who is he then?

673
00:52:46,840 --> 00:52:48,729
Good fucking question.

674
00:52:49,000 --> 00:52:50,809
See, he's an agency man.

675
00:52:51,000 --> 00:52:53,367
He was brought in during Vietnam.

676
00:52:53,560 --> 00:52:56,086
See, he put together this team,
this special team...

677
00:52:56,280 --> 00:52:57,964
...that only answered
to the president.

678
00:52:58,520 --> 00:53:00,045
Brooks was my mentor.

679
00:53:00,240 --> 00:53:03,801
Brought us all in from nothing.
Taught us how to fight.

680
00:53:04,000 --> 00:53:05,889
Taught us about loyalty and honour.

681
00:53:06,280 --> 00:53:10,649
Made us believe we was finally doing
something right in our fucked-up lives.

682
00:53:11,160 --> 00:53:12,764
What a joke.

683
00:53:13,440 --> 00:53:15,681
Then there was this operation
called London Fog.

684
00:53:16,600 --> 00:53:19,570
<i>It was a nasty little gig
during Desert storm...</i>

685
00:53:19,880 --> 00:53:22,724
<i>...headed by our old friend,
Mr. Darryl Greene.</i>

686
00:53:22,920 --> 00:53:25,241
That was back
when he worked for the CIA.

687
00:53:25,440 --> 00:53:28,091
See, the agency had developed
this little nerve gas...

688
00:53:28,280 --> 00:53:30,009
<i>...they called CMC-12.</i>

689
00:53:30,200 --> 00:53:32,009
<i>A thousand times
more deadly than sarin.</i>

690
00:53:32,520 --> 00:53:33,885
<i>And during the end of the war...</i>

691
00:53:34,080 --> 00:53:37,687
<i>...the entire Iraq army--
They was hauling ass out of Kuwait.</i>

692
00:53:37,880 --> 00:53:39,325
<i>You know what Greene wants to do?</i>

693
00:53:40,520 --> 00:53:43,524
He decides to have
a little field test on the CMC-12.

694
00:53:43,720 --> 00:53:44,801
- What?
- Yeah...

695
00:53:45,000 --> 00:53:48,925
<i>...before there was any chance of talks
for a cease-fire or anything like that.</i>

696
00:53:49,440 --> 00:53:50,965
<i>So we dropped a container.</i>

697
00:53:51,480 --> 00:53:53,847
<i>- What?
- Took out an army platoon.</i>

698
00:53:54,040 --> 00:53:57,487
<i>But also killed every man, woman
and child within a mile radius.</i>

699
00:53:57,680 --> 00:53:58,681
<i>Jesus.</i>

700
00:53:58,880 --> 00:54:00,120
And the thermos?

701
00:54:00,600 --> 00:54:01,886
Thermos?

702
00:54:02,080 --> 00:54:05,129
It got ten times the CMC-12
than what was dropped in Iraq.

703
00:54:05,320 --> 00:54:07,163
Oh, my God.

704
00:54:07,360 --> 00:54:09,408
What do you think
he's gonna do with it?

705
00:54:09,600 --> 00:54:11,568
Who the fuck knows?

706
00:54:11,760 --> 00:54:14,047
But I'll tell you one thing, mama.

707
00:54:14,240 --> 00:54:18,564
If we don't find him,
we can kiss all our asses goodbye.

708
00:54:33,400 --> 00:54:35,402
Barnes.

709
00:54:37,360 --> 00:54:38,646
Brooks called.

710
00:54:38,840 --> 00:54:41,411
He wants $22 million and safe
passage to a neutral country...

711
00:54:41,600 --> 00:54:43,887
...or he'll set off CMC-12
in the middle of the city.

712
00:54:44,080 --> 00:54:45,366
Fuck.

713
00:54:45,560 --> 00:54:46,891
Okay, I will...

714
00:54:47,080 --> 00:54:49,890
I will notify the president
and get him to a safe location.

715
00:54:50,080 --> 00:54:52,606
That is exactly
what we're not going to do.

716
00:54:52,800 --> 00:54:55,041
We keep this all in-house.
Let's not panic.

717
00:54:55,240 --> 00:54:56,207
Okay.

718
00:54:56,400 --> 00:54:58,846
You know Brooks better than I do,
but I don't understand.

719
00:54:59,040 --> 00:55:02,647
Why 22 million, and why CMC-12?

720
00:55:02,840 --> 00:55:04,524
In a warped way
it makes perfect sense.

721
00:55:04,720 --> 00:55:07,326
This is Billy Brooks' big "fuck you"
to me and the government.

722
00:55:07,520 --> 00:55:10,126
His annual operating
budget was 22 mil.

723
00:55:10,320 --> 00:55:12,402
CMC-12 was my project.

724
00:55:12,600 --> 00:55:14,807
It's a project
that's not supposed to exist.

725
00:55:15,000 --> 00:55:18,322
What matters now is we get the
CMC-12 back and buried.

726
00:55:18,520 --> 00:55:22,081
We'll play his game and then we'll
take down Brooks before this gets out.

